Downloading data

1. Use tidycensus to download 1. race/ethnicity (B03002) and 2. median household income for Baltimore City. Store this data in a new object. Choose which race/ethnicity youd like to relate to income (Non-Hispanic Black and Non-Hispanic White work best). Which census tract has the highest percentage of your target race/ethnicity (and what is the percent) and which has the highest median household income (and how much is it?)? (5 points) Reminder: Since we will be mapping our data, make sure you include use geometry = TRUE in get_acs()

# Download total population, population of Blacks, and median household income ACS 2019 Census data from https://www.socialexplorer.com/data/ACS2019_5yr/metadata/?ds=ACS19_5yr for Maine tracts.
Balt_income_race = get_acs(geography = "tract",
      variables = c("total_pop" = "B03002_001",# Total population
                    "Blck_NonH" = "B03002_004", # Non-Hispanic Black population
                    "income" = "B19013_001"), # Median household income
      year = 2019,
survey = "acs5",
state = c(24),  # FIPS code for Maryland
county = c(510), # FIPS code for Baltimore City
geometry = TRUE,
output = "wide")

3. Create two plots. In the first plot highlight the tract with the highest concentration of your selected race/eth. In the second plot highlight the tract with the highest median household income? (5 points)

library(dplyr)

# Define a variable equivalent to the tract with the highest Black percentage.
Max_percent = Balt_income_race %>%
  filter(Percent_Blck == max(Percent_Blck, na.rm = TRUE)) 

ggplot(Balt_income_race) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cut_number(Percent_Blck, 4))) +
  geom_sf(data = Max_percent, color = "yellow", fill = "yellow") +
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "seq", palette = 1,
                    name = "Percent of Pop that is Black") +
  labs(title = "Percent of Baltimore City's Non-Hispanic Black Population") +
  xlab("Longitude") +
  ylab("Latitude") +
  theme_bw()

# Define a variable equivalent to the tract with the highest median income.
Max_income = Balt_income_race %>%
  filter(incomeE == max(incomeE, na.rm = TRUE)) 

ggplot(Balt_income_race) + 
  geom_sf(aes(fill = cut_number(incomeE, 4))) +
  geom_sf(data = Max_income, color = "yellow", fill = "yellow") +
  scale_fill_brewer(type = "seq", palette = 1,
                    name = "Median Household Income") +
  labs(title = "Median Household Income in Baltimore City") +
  xlab("Longitude") +
  ylab("Latitude") +
  theme_bw()

5. Create a bivariate map with your data. (3 points)

# create map
bivariate = ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = Balt_income_race, mapping = aes(fill = bi_class), color = "white", size = 0.1, show.legend = FALSE) +
  bi_scale_fill(pal = "DkViolet", dim = 3) +
  labs(title = "Income and Percent Black People in Baltimore City",
    subtitle = "Dark Violet Palette") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size=12))
  bi_theme()
plot(bivariate)

6. Use the cowplot package and ggdraw, like in the tutorial to add a legend (2 points).

# Create the legend
legend = bi_legend(pal = "DkViolet",
                    dim = 3,
                    xlab = " Higher % NonHis Black ",
                    ylab = " Higher Income ",
                    size = 8)

# Install cowplot if you haven't already 
library(cowplot)
## Warning: package 'cowplot' was built under R version 4.0.5
Final_map = ggdraw() +
  draw_plot(bivariate, 0, 0, .8, 1) +
  draw_plot(legend, .70, .15, 0.35, 0.35)

plot(Final_map)

3. Reflection (3 points)

When I compare this lab to the last one, which shared many similarities, Im impressed by how much a difficult lab can teach you. This lab went much smoother for me than the last and I attribute that to what I learned from the previous one. I had to alter my method from before for part 2 because using max(Balt_income_race$Percent_Blck, na.rm = TRUE) would cut the returned value at a certain number of decimals but I needed the whole thing if I was to use subset(). So I instead used filter() combined with max() which worked even better. The next obstacle was figuring out how to highlight certain tracts which only required defining a variable and an extra geom_sf() line with a different color fill. Python and R Tips was a useful guide. The last new obstacle was creating bivariates in R instead of QGIS. I had to play around with what data classification method I used but with the tutorial at hand I didnt face much difficulty. Its quite a powerful tool, faster than QGIS, and something I will surely use again.

I had no major issues in QGIS safe for after I exported the web map. It had no legend and it took much trial and error in notepad working on that code before I managed to not only include a photo of the legend, but position it correctly. After that I had to look up how to position the layers because my legend was set behind the base map, giving it a transparent look which isnt useful for comparing colors. I learned that I could set the base maps z-index to a negative value to place it in the background and the rest was uploading it to GitHub, which I now have practice in.

In regards to the data, I dont believe there was much to be surprised about for Baltimore City. The red tracts, representing dense populations of Black people and low income, resembled the famous Black Butterfly pattern. When compared to Howard County the city house a much larger percentage of Black people and, although the values arent depicted in the maps, appears much more wealthy. What Im most glad to learn from this lab is that Ive made noticable progress. Its an inspiring thought.
